@woohoo1215 Under the terms of the deal, Iran is required to allow the IAEA access to any military site within 24 days of the request. The reason Iran's military sites had not been inspected is because the IAEA never asked. If they did and Iran refused, that would be a violation of the deal.

@woohoo1215 24 days is pretty short when part of the deal was that Iran was required to reduce their Uranium stockpile to the point where it would take them a year to develop a bomb. The deal was effective in the sense that it made it harder for them to get nukes.

@woohoo1215 I'm not going to argue that the deal was perfect. But leaving did not get us a better deal. Instead, leaving the deal created a dangerous cycle of escalation, encouraged Iran to ramp up their nuclear program, and gave them a reason not to trust us in future negotiations.
@DaBikeRichie @SenMcSallyAZ Clearly, this is a less regulated Iran than when we were in the deal. Trump's policies towards Iran make the world a more dangerous place.

@woohoo1215 Also, leaving the deal did not put us in a better position in this regard. Those military sites are still not inspected, and Iran is now blatantly violating the original terms of the deal. Even though the deal wasn't perfect, having no deal is significantly more dangerous

@DaBikeRichie @SenMcSallyAZ The Iranian government isn't perfect, but the way to check them is through diplomacy, not military action. It is easily observable that the situation in Iran is worse now than it was when we upheld the Iran Nuclear Deal.

@woohoo1215 That being said, it's a good thing for Iran to rebuild its economy. Most of the people hurt by sanctions are middle class Iranians who have nothing to do with foreign policy. Many of them even view America and its values favorably

@woohoo1215 Also, Trump's actions did more than just reveal Iran's "true colors." They made the situation a lot worse a lot quicker than it had to be. The deal was doing a good job of stopping Iran's nuclear program.

@DaBikeRichie @SenMcSallyAZ While we were part of the Iran nuclear deal, Iran followed it too, reducing their uranium stockholds, and definitely not shooting down airplanes. You don't have to take Iran's word for that, the IAEA, an international third party watchdog, confirmed that as recently as Feb 2019.
